{[%evp 0,36,25,27,27,27,31,13,14,14,30,-53,-53,-62,-62,-62,-62,-62,-16,-82,-86,
-86,-86,-86,-10,-72,-72,-72,-72,-66,-55,-161,58,-351,-351,-439,-415,-401,-624]
} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nf5 {The idea of this move is
quite simple, White wants to play the bishop to e3, trade bishops and place
the knight on the ideal e3-square. As we have already seen, this is a great
spot for the knight. If we compare this to the 5.Be3 & 7.Nc2 line, we can
appreciate that White is looking to save himself some tempi (no need to c2-c3).
The theory considers this to be one of White's weakest sidelines since the idea
seems to fail tactically. However, as we'll see, Black should not overestimate
his position.} d5 $1 {the knight on f5 is vulnerable and this doesn't give
White enough time to trade the bishops} ({White's idea can be fully
appreciated after the normal-looking} 5... g6 $6 6. Be3 Bb6 (6... Bxe3 7. Nxe3
$14 {[%csl Ge3]}) 7. Bxb6 axb6 8. Ne3 $14 {[%csl Ge3]}) 6. Nxg7+ (6. Qxd5 $2
Qxd5 7. exd5 Nb4 8. Be3 Bxf5 9. Bxc5 Nxc2+ 10. Kd2 Nxa1 11. Nc3 O-O-O $19) (6.
exd5 $2 Bxf5 7. dxc6 Bxf2+ 8. Ke2 Bg4+ $19) (6. Nc3 Bxf5 7. exf5 Nf6 8. Bg5 O-O
9. Be2 (9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Qxd5 Rfe8+ 11. Be2 Bb4 $19) 9... Re8 10. O-O Nd4 {
[%cal Gc7c6] It's already White who should think about equality.}) (6. Be3 d4
$1 ({the engine is actually not too enthusiastic about winning the pawn right
away with} 6... Bxe3 7. Nxe3 dxe4 (7... d4 $5) 8. Qxd8+ Nxd8 9. Nc3 Nf6 10.
O-O-O $44) 7. Bf4 Bxf5 8. exf5 Qd5 $17) 6... Kf8 7. Nh5 (7. Nf5 $2 Bxf5 8. exf5
Qh4 9. Qf3 Re8+ 10. Kd1 (10. Be2 Nd4 $19) 10... Nf6 $19 {Black has an
overwhelming compensation for the pawn and the broken up kingside structure.
The massive lead in development gives Black a winning position. For example}
11. g3 (11. Be3 Bxe3 12. fxe3 Ng4 13. g3 Qg5 $19) (11. Nc3 Ne5 (11... Ne4 $5)
12. Qg3 Qd4+ 13. Bd2 Rg8 14. Qf4 Qxf4 15. Bxf4 Neg4 16. Bg3 Bxf2 $19) 11...
Qd4+ 12. Bd3 Ne5 $19) 7... Qh4 8. Ng3 Nf6 $1 {Black should not hurry to
recover the pawn since this gives white the possibility to start creating
some threats of his own and in the process catch up with development} (8...
dxe4 $6 9. Qd5 {[%cal Rc1g5,Rd5c5]} Bb6 10. Bg5 $16) 9. Be2 ({A nice
illustration of how bad things can get for White can bee seen after} 9. exd5 $2
Ng4 10. dxc6 (10. Be3 Bxe3 11. fxe3 Nxh2 $19) 10... Bxf2+ 11. Kd2 {Black is
winning and there is more than one way to continue.} Nxh2 $5 (11... Qh6+ $5 {
[%cal Rh6c6]}) 12. Qh5 Qxg3 13. Qh6+ Ke8 14. Bd3 (14. Qxh2 Qe3+ 15. Kd1 Qe1#)
14... Ng4 15. Qg7 Rf8 16. Kc3 Be6 17. cxb7 Rd8 18. Bh6 c5 $3 $19 {the threat
of ...Bd4 ends the game} 19. Kd2 (19. Qxf8+ Kd7 20. Qg7 Bd4+ $19) 19... Be3+
20. Bxe3 Qxe3+ 21. Kc3 Ne5 22. b3 Qd4+ 23. Kd2 Nc4+ 24. bxc4 Qxg7 $19) 9...
dxe4 {Now that the d5-square has been taken under control it's safe to
recapture the pawn. In the arising position, the material balance has been
restored, but Black's pawn structure and king safety have been undermined.
However, these factors pale in comparison to the lead in development and piece
activity Black has achieved. Black will continue with ...Be6 followed by ...
Rd8 and should white castle, then the idea ...h5 followed by ...Ng4 (trying to
get the h-file opened) is particularly strong.} 10. Be3 $1 {this is white's
most flexible move, preparing 0-0-0} (10. Nc3 Be6 11. Be3 Bxe3 $1 {normally
Black wants to refrain from this capture, but otherwise white will have enough
time to castle queenside} (11... Bd6 $2 12. Qd2 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1,Re3g5]}) 12.
fxe3 Rd8 13. Qc1 Ne5 $40 {[%cal Rh8g8,Re5g4]}) (10. O-O $6 {Castling into
Black's attack is a bad idea} h5 $1 $40 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Rf6g4,Rh8h1]} 11. Be3
(11. h3 Qxg3 $19) (11. Nc3 Ng4 12. h3 Qxg3 13. Bxg4 hxg4 14. Nxe4 Qe5 $19)
11... Bd6 $1 {since there is no danger that White will castle queenside, Black
can avoid the trade} 12. Qd2 (12. Bd4 Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Rh7 {[%cal Rf6g4]} 14. Nc3
Ng4 15. h3 e3 $19) 12... Ng4 13. h3 Nxe3 14. Qxe3 Bxh3 $1 15. gxh3 Rg8 16. Kh2
Nd4 {[%cal Rd4f5]} 17. Rg1 Nf5 18. Qb3 e3 $19) 10... Bxe3 (10... Bd6 $6 11. Qd2
Rg8 12. Nc3 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1]}) (10... Bb6 11. Qd2 Rg8 12. Nc3 Be6 13. O-O-O
$14) 11. fxe3 {This is the critical position of the variation. White has a
nice clamp on dark-squares, so Black must act swiftly before white
consolidates his position.} Bg4 {Intending to trade bishops first and only
then play the knight to g4} (11... Ng4 $2 12. Bxg4 Bxg4 13. Qd5 $16) (11... Be6
$6 12. O-O $1 h5 13. Rf4 Ng4 14. Bxg4 hxg4 15. Nc3 Qxh2+ 16. Kf2 $16 {White
will regain the pawn with great dark square control.}) (11... h5 {this move
works much better once White has already castled kingside.} 12. Nc3 (12. Qd2 $5
Be6 13. Qc3 Rd8 14. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Ge1c1]}) 12... Be6 13. O-O Rd8 (13... Ng4
14. Bxg4 hxg4 15. Rf4 Qxh2+ 16. Kf2 $44) 14. Qe1 Ng4 15. Bxg4 hxg4 16. Rf4
Qxh2+ 17. Kf2 $44) 12. O-O (12. Nc3 Rd8 13. Qc1 Ne5 $15) (12. Nd2 Rg8 13. O-O
Bxe2 14. Qxe2 Ng4 15. h3 Qxg3 16. hxg4 Rxg4 $17) (12. Bxg4 $2 Nxg4 13. Qe2 Nxh2
14. Qf2 Nd4 $3 15. Nc3 (15. exd4 e3 $19) 15... Nxc2+ 16. Qxc2 Qxg3+ 17. Qf2
Qxf2+ 18. Kxf2 Ng4+ $17) 12... Bxe2 ({Black can also insert the moves} 12...
Rd8 $5 13. Nd2 (13. Qe1 Bxe2 14. Nxe2 Qxe1 15. Rxe1 Nb4 16. Na3 Rg8 17. Rad1
Ke7 18. Nf4 Rxd1 19. Rxd1 Rd8 20. Rxd8 Kxd8 $17) 13... Bxe2 (13... h5 14. Rf4)
14. Qxe2 Ng4 15. h3 Qxg3 16. hxg4 Ne5 17. Rf4 Rxd2 18. Qxd2 Nf3+ 19. Rxf3 exf3
20. Qd8+ Kg7 21. Qg5+ Kf8 $11) 13. Qxe2 Ng4 14. h3 (14. Rf4 $2 Qxh2+ 15. Kf1
Nce5 $19) 14... Qxg3 15. Qxg4 Qxg4 (15... Qxe3+ 16. Kh1 Rg8 17. Qf5 Rg7 18. Nc3
$44) 16. hxg4 Rg8 17. Rf4 (17. Nc3 Rxg4 18. Rad1 Re8 $15) 17... Ne5 18. Nc3 Rd8
$11 *

