{[%evp 0,102,16,37,38,28,28,28,-15,-5,28,28,20,6,-24,-22,-33,-33,25,-2,34,15,
-16,-26,-11,-8,-4,-36,-19,-22,-26,-18,-26,-17,-11,-11,-4,-13,37,36,29,30,33,32,
36,24,48,16,13,-2,-7,-26,-10,-18,-15,-38,-33,-35,-44,-50,-50,-42,-31,-60,-78,
-95,-52,-72,-75,-74,-67,-124,-120,-183,-183,-183,-191,-175,-175,-212,-168,-165,
-165,-160,-161,-207,-188,-286,-178,-191,-185,-185,-207,-291,-312,-338,-369,
-591,-654,-1192,-1269,-1283,-681,-1151,-1327]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4
4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Be3 Qf6 6. Nb5 Bxe3 7. fxe3 Qh4+ 8. g3 {Many years ago (and
even recently) I was tempted to play the more calm and positionally conscious
8...Qd8!?. The point being that Black will repel White's initiative and enjoy
the much better pawn structure. However, as practice (and most importantly
engine analysis) has shown, White's initiative is not so easy to contain!
Therefore, Black should charge into the breach! As often occurs, this courage
will be amply rewarded as can be seen in the analysis that follows.} Qxe4 $1 {
Black should not shy away from the complications. Each side will be able to
capture a rook, but the black queen will have a much easier time escaping from
h1 than the white knight from a8.} 9. Nxc7+ Kd8 10. Nxa8 Nf6 $1 {The white
rook on h1 isn't going anywhere, so it's better to bring more pieces into play
while limiting some of White's options.} 11. Qd6 ({An interesting try is} 11.
Nc3 Qxh1 12. Qd2 (12. Qd6 {- transposes to 11.Qd6}) 12... Re8 $5 ({In
principle, Black should prevent White from castling queenside. In this case,
it would seem White has nothing better than to repeat moves. However, I think
Black can hope for more} 12... Qf3 13. Be2 Qh1+ 14. Bf1 $11) 13. O-O-O Qf3 14.
e4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Qxe4 16. Qg5+ f6 17. Qxg7 Qg6 18. Qxg6 hxg6 $19 {and even
though White restored the material balance, the knight on a8 is doomed. Black
had no trouble capitalizing on this in the game 0-1 (39) Martinez de Negri, G 
(2211)-Pierrot,F (2379) Buenos Aires ARG 2018}) (11. Rg1 $2 Qxe3+ $19) 11...
Qxh1 12. Nc3 (12. Nd2 $5 {[%csl Gf3][%cal Gd2f3] Preventing ...Qf3 and thus
preparing to castle queenside makes a lot of sense. Black must act quickly} Ne8
{A thematic idea, removing the queen from the annoying d6-square while taking
control over the c7-square as well} 13. Qf4 Qxh2 14. O-O-O Qh6 15. Qxf7 Qxe3
16. Bg2 (16. Kb1 Qe7 17. Qf2 Rf8 18. Qg1 d5 19. Bb5 Bf5 $17) 16... Qxg3 $17 {
was nevertheless desperate for white in the game Olafsson, T (2184)-Kjartansson,
G (2442) Reykjavik 2016}) (12. Qc7+ Ke7 13. Nc3 (13. Nd2 $2 Nd5 $19) 13... Qf3
$1 {once again we encounter this thematic idea, preventing quite from castling
queenside} 14. Qf4 Qxf4 15. exf4 Kd8 16. O-O-O Re8 ({Another possibility is} 
16... d5 $5 17. Nxd5 Bg4 18. Rd2 Nxd5 19. Rxd5+ Kc8 20. Rg5 Be6 21. Rxg7 Kb8
$15) 17. Bc4 Re7 18. a3 b6 19. Nb5 Bb7 $19 {and White did not manage to save
his knight in the game Tripi, N (1976)-Lesiege, A (2521) Menton 2016}) (12. Nc7
$2 Ne4 13. Qf4 g5 $19 {and White loses the knight}) 12... Qf3 $1 {The secret
to Black's success in this position lies in preventing White from castling
queenside and maintaining the queens on the board.} ({Bad is} 12... Ne4 $2 {
in view of} 13. Qc7+ Ke7 (13... Ke8 14. Qxc8+) 14. Nd5+ Ke6 15. O-O-O {and
White is winning.}) 13. Qf4 {this is a serious compromise for White since
without queens the fate of the knight on a8 is quite uncertain.} (13. Nc7 $2
Qxe3+ 14. Be2 Ne5 $19 {[%cal Re5f3]}) (13. Be2 Qxe3 14. Rd1 Ne8 15. Qd5 Ne5 16.
Kf1 d6 $19 {[%cal Rc8h3]}) (13. Kd2 Ne8 $17 {[%csl Ra8]}) (13. Qc7+ Ke7 14. Qf4
{- transposes to 12.Qc7}) 13... Qxf4 14. gxf4 b6 15. Nb5 $8 (15. O-O-O Bb7 16.
Nxb6 axb6 $19) 15... Rf8 $1 {A nice prophylactic move, after which the knight
on a8 is trapped.} 16. Nac7 (16. Nd6 Ne8 $19) (16. Nbc7 Bb7 17. O-O-O Ke7 $19)
16... a6 $19 {Black wins a piece.} *

