{[%evp 0,62,19,11,38,36,18,28,28,-9,28,28,24,24,24,-7,-43,-40,30,45,44,50,50,
52,47,47,65,50,58,28,47,42,40,33,45,35,37,39,59,65,92,38,13,25,105,104,104,54,
47,51,56,64,84,-59,-73,-70,-61,-50,-54,-68,-50,-89,-83,-67,-70]} 1. e4 e5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Be3 Qf6 6. c3 Nge7 7. g3 h5 $5 {The 7.g3
used to be a very popular choice for positional players that did not
necessarily aim for a big advantage in the opening, but rather a nagging clamp
on Black's centre (preventing the ...d7-d5 pawn break at all costs). This
worked well for a while, but after 7...h5 it seems White cannot ignore Black's
play along the h-file and must do something to diffuse it. Whether white plays
8.h3 d5 or 8.h4 d5, this will likely lead to worse versions for white given
the weakened kingside.} 8. h4 {White decides to fix Black's h-pawn, but this
weakness the very important g4-square} ({The ambitious} 8. f4 {runs into the
thematic} d5 $1 9. Qd2 (9. e5 Qh6 10. Qd2 h4 11. Rg1 (11. f5 Qh7 $17) 11...
hxg3 12. hxg3 Bg4 $15) 9... dxe4 10. Nb5 Bd6 11. c4 {[%cal Gc4c5] It seems
that White has managed to develop a dangerous initiative since c4-c5 is coming.
Black, however, has a wonderful resource:} Bg4 12. c5 Be5 $3 {An amusing line
would be:} 13. fxe5 Nxe5 14. Nxc7+ Kf8 15. Qd6 Qf3 16. Qxe5 (16. Nd5 N5c6 17.
Rg1 Qd1+ 18. Kf2 Rd8 $19) 16... Qxe3+ 17. Be2 Qxe2#) (8. Bg2 h4 9. O-O (9. Na3
Bxa3 (9... a6 $5) 10. bxa3 a6 11. O-O d6 12. f4 hxg3 13. hxg3 Qg6 14. Kf2 Bg4
$15 {[%cal Ge8c8] led to a ferocious attack for Black in the game Brunello, M 
(2259)-Dvirnyy,D (2560) Padova 2013}) 9... hxg3 10. hxg3 (10. fxg3 Qg6 11. Nd2
Ne5 $40 {[%cal Re5g4,Rd7d6] now the knight joins the attack}) 10... Ne5 {
The following games and variations support the conclusion that Black's attack
already looks overwhelming.} ({It turns out that} 10... d6 $5 {is also
playable. A possible continuation would be} 11. Nb5 (11. Na3 Ne5 $17) 11...
Bxe3 12. fxe3 (12. Nxc7+ Kf8 13. fxe3 Qh6 14. Nxa8 Ne5 $19 {[%csl Rg1][%cal
Re5g4]}) 12... Qh6 $1 $40 {Black's attack is very dangerous.}) 11. Qe2 ({
As usual, the move} 11. f4 {turns out to be premature.} Nc4 12. Qe2 d5 (12...
Nxe3 13. Qxe3 d5 $17) 13. e5 Qg6 14. Bf2 Bxd4 15. cxd4 Bg4 16. Qe1 Qh7 17. Be3
Qh2+ 18. Kf2 Nf5 $19 {Black is winning.}) (11. Nc2 d6 12. Bxc5 (12. Nd2 g5 13.
f4 gxf4 14. gxf4 Ng4 15. Bxc5 dxc5 $19) 12... Qh6 $1 $19 {A devastating
in-between move that soon ended the game in Hrabinska, M (2277)-Bhat, V (2495)
Cappelle-la-Grande 2009}) 11... d6 12. f3 Qg6 13. Kf2 Rh2 14. Rh1 Rxh1 15. Bxh1
Bd7 $17 {Black simply intend to castle queenside and open up the f-file by
means of ...f7-f5, as was seen in the game Pambalos, P (2123)-Pavlidis, A (2278)
Greece 2009}) (8. h3 {White is ready to answer ...h5-h4 with g3-g4. In this
case, however, Black has time to strike in the centre.} d5 {One of the
critical positions arises after} 9. Bg2 Bxd4 10. cxd4 dxe4 11. Nc3 Be6 12. Nxe4
Qf5 {[%cal Ge6d5] Now Black will place the bishop on d5 in the hope that this
will eventually lead to a trade of light-squared bishop. This would be the
ultimate accomplishment for Black since it would leave White's kingside in
shambles.} 13. Nc3 (13. O-O O-O-O (13... Bd5 $5 14. Qc2 O-O-O $15) 14. Qa4 Bd5
15. Nc5 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Qd5+ 17. Kh2 Nf5 $17 {led to a light square catastrophy
for white in the game Schneider,V (2294)-Gonda,L (2538) Budapest 2013}) 13...
O-O-O 14. O-O Nd5 15. Rc1 (15. Ne4 Qg6 16. Nc5 Nxe3 17. fxe3 Qxg3 $17 {Black
is up a pawn and the white king has been severely exposed}) 15... Nxc3 $1 (
15... Rhe8 16. Ne4 $40 {[%cal Ge4c5]}) 16. bxc3 Bd5 $11 {Black has solved all
the major problems and is prepared to trade off the light-squared bishops. It
is white who must tread with caution now}) (8. Nc2 {White argues that the
inclusion of the moves 7.g3 h5 can lead to a favourable version of the 7.Nc2
line} d6 $1 {This idea is quite interesting against the 7.Nc2 variation, but
here it is particularly strong given Black's pressure on the kingside} ({
White's idea can be clearly appreciated after} 8... Bb6 9. Nba3 O-O $2 10. Qxh5
$16) 9. Bg2 ({After} 9. Bxc5 {Black can develop a dangerous kingside
initiative.} dxc5 10. Ne3 Be6 11. Bg2 ({White is not in time to prevent ...
h5-h4 with} 11. h4 {After} Ne5 12. Bg2 Bg4 13. Nxg4 hxg4 $15 {[%csl Ge5]
Black's powerful knight in the centre gives him an obvious advantage.}) 11...
h4 {Black's pressure is annoying.}) ({In response to} 9. h4 {Black can go for}
Bg4 10. Be2 Ne5 $15 {[%cal Ge8c8] with an initiative.}) (9. h3 $6 {allows
Black to weaken the dark squares by means of} h4 10. g4 Bxe3 11. Nxe3 Ne5 $15 {
[%csl Gf4]}) 9... h4 10. Qe2 {This is the most cautious reaction.} (10. Nd2 $6
Ne5 11. Qe2 (11. f4 $2 Nd3+ $19) 11... Bg4 12. f3 h3 $1 13. fxg4 (13. Bf1 Nxf3+
$19) 13... hxg2 14. Qxg2 {0-1 (37) Ulanowski,K (2133)-Eingorn,V (2548) Bad
Wiessee 2013} Nd3+ 15. Ke2 Nxb2 16. Bd4 Qe6 $19) 10... Be6 (10... Ne5 $6 11. f4
$14) 11. Nd2 h3 (11... Qg6 12. f4 hxg3 13. f5 $16) 12. Bf1 g5 13. O-O-O O-O-O
$15 {White's f2-f4 advance has been contained while Black retains the more
active position.}) 8... d5 9. Bg2 Bg4 {Black is happy to provoke the move
f2-f3 since it would hinder the bishop on g2 as well as weaken the g3-pawn}
10. Qa4 (10. Qb3 Nxd4 11. cxd4 Bxd4 12. Bxd4 Qxd4 13. O-O dxe4 14. Nc3 O-O 15.
Qxb7 f5 $15 {Black is up a pawn, but most importantly the bishop on g2 has
been shut down. Black went on to convert his advantage in the game
Vaicekauskas, G (2210)-Meskovs, N (2538) Katowice 2017}) (10. f3 Bd7 11. O-O Qg6
(11... O-O-O $5 $15) 12. Kh2 Bd6 13. f4 dxe4 14. Nd2 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 f5 $17 {
and Black went on to convert his extra pawn in the game Kislov, M (2363)
-Schwarz, D (2292) Frydek Mistek 2008}) 10... Bd7 11. Qd1 O-O-O ({Black should
not get tempted to go for the e4-pawn since White's position is set up for
exactly this} 11... Bxd4 $6 12. cxd4 dxe4 13. Nc3 Nf5 14. Nxe4 $14 {0-1 (52)
Murray, D (2120)-Arnaudov, P (2484) Rogaska Slatina 2011}) ({Another way Black
can lose his way is with} 11... Nxd4 $6 12. cxd4 Bb4+ 13. Nc3 dxe4 14. O-O Bxc3
15. bxc3 $44 {0-1 (50) Henry,F (1814)-Delorme,A (2442) Sautron 2009}) 12. Nxc6
(12. O-O dxe4 13. Nd2 Bg4 14. Qa4 Nxd4 15. cxd4 Bxd4 16. Nxe4 Qb6 $17 {looks
like a healthy extra pawn for Black.}) 12... Qxc6 13. exd5 Qb5 14. Bxc5 (14. a4
Qxb2 15. Bxc5 Qxa1 16. O-O Nf5 $17 {White hoped the bishop pair would provide
enough compensation for the material imbalance, but I simply don't see a way
for White's initiative to get off the ground}) 14... Bg4 $3 {After this move
the position is blown open and the white king comes under heavy fire} 15. Na3 (
15. f3 Qxc5 16. fxg4 Rhe8 17. Kf1 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Rxd5 $19) 15... Qxc5 16. Qd2
Nf5 $1 (16... Nxd5 17. O-O $15) 17. O-O Nxg3 $17 {While material might remain
even, the white king has been stripped of a key pawn and has an uphill battle
ahead of him} *

