{[%evp 0,26,28,34,37,27,0,-15,-15,-15,41,41,17,31,17,12,25,-9,-16,-18,-1,-108,
-101,-117,-168,-160,-160,-168,-206]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5
5. Be3 Qf6 6. c3 Nge7 7. Be2 {White plays for rapid kingside development, but
this neglects control over the d5-square} (7. Bb5 {Just like in the 7.Be2 line,
White aims for a quick kingside development followed by f2-f4. But unlike the
aforementioned line, by putting pressure on c6, white hopes to deter the ...
d7-d5 advance} O-O 8. O-O d6 ({With a bishop on b5, the advance} 8... d5 $6 {
does not work so well:} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Bxc5 cxb5 11. e5 $14 {White keeps a
slight pressure in this position.}) (8... Bb6 9. a4 d5 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. a5 Bc5
12. Nd2 $14 {Black's pawn structure was problematic. 1-0 (35) Beerdsen,T (2477)
-Petkidis,A (2375) Skopje 2018}) 9. f4 Bb6 10. Qd2 (10. Kh1 d5 11. e5 Qh6 12.
Qd2 Nxd4 13. cxd4 Nf5 14. Bf2 f6 $13 {Da Silva Filho,A (2031)-Vorobiev,A (2020)
email 2009}) 10... Nxd4 {Black is ready for this typical exchange. After} 11.
cxd4 d5 12. e5 Qg6 13. Nc3 c6 14. Be2 h5 $13 {we reach a typical structure in
which Black manages to establish a blockade on the light squares. Warzecha, H 
(2439)-Leisebein,P (2455) email 2014}) (7. Qd2 {White surrenders the d5-square,
but by protecting the bishop he prepares to attack black's vulnerable c7 pawn}
d5 (7... O-O 8. Nb5 Bxe3 9. Qxe3 d5 {- 7...d5}) 8. Nb5 {the point behind 7.Qd2}
(8. Nxc6 Bxe3 9. Qxe3 Qxc6 10. Nd2 Be6 $11) 8... Bxe3 9. Qxe3 O-O 10. Nd2 (10.
Nxc7 Rb8 $44 {White has won the c7-pawn but is seriously behind in
development and the future of the c7-knight is far from certain. The following
variations seem to support the assessment that White's position hangs by a
thread} 11. Nxd5 (11. Nd2 dxe4 12. O-O-O Bg4 13. Be2 Bxe2 14. Qxe2 a6 15. Qxe4
Qd6 $19) (11. exd5 Nf5 12. Qf4 Ne5 13. Qb4 Qd8 14. d6 Nxd6 15. Nd5 Re8 16. Ne3
Ng4 $19 {0-1 (23) Dembo,Y (2482)-Lagno,K (2483) Novi Sad 2009}) 11... Nxd5 12.
exd5 Nb4 $1 13. Qd2 Re8+ 14. Be2 Bg4 15. f3 Nxd5 16. O-O Nf4 17. Bd1 Rbd8 18.
Qf2 Bh3 {0-1 (18) Lupu,M (2430)-Miles,A (2590) Cappelle-la-Grande 1994}) 10...
Bd7 $1 {This forces White to prove the worth of his idea. If he refuses to
capture the c7-pawn, then Black will simply protect it by means of ...Rac8 and
then drive away the white knight} (10... dxe4 11. Nxe4 Qe5 12. Nc5 Qxe3+ 13.
fxe3 $36 {was successfully employed by Rublevsky on more than one occasion.
Despite the damaged pawn structure, White has serious pressure on the queenside
}) 11. Nxc7 (11. O-O-O {allows} Rac8 {Black has better development and more
secured king.} 12. Bd3 Ne5 13. Nf3 Ng4 14. Qe2 Ng6 15. e5 N4xe5 16. Nxe5 Nxe5
17. Bc2 c6 $19 {0-1 (20) Barbot,P (2232)-Gozzoli,Y (2532) Creon 2011}) ({
Too slow is} 11. Be2 Rac8 12. O-O Rfe8 $15 {White is under pressure.}) 11...
Rac8 12. exd5 (12. Nb5 Nf5 $1 13. Qh3 dxe4 $17) 12... Nb4 13. cxb4 Rxc7 14. Be2
Nxd5 15. Qf3 Nf4 $19) (7. Qf3 $6 Nxd4 8. Qxf6 (8. Bxd4 Bxd4 9. cxd4 Qxd4 10.
Nc3 O-O $17 {0-1 (43) Kirzhatskih,A-Vasiliev,N (2370) Ekaterinburg 2000}) 8...
Nc2+ 9. Kd2 Bxe3+ 10. fxe3 gxf6 11. Kxc2 Ng6 $15 {both sides have doubled
isolated pawns, but White's are arguably weaker. This is due to the fact that
they are more advanced and limit the scope of the f1-bishop. Black won
convincingly in the game 0-1 (61) Ebeling, M (2273)-Nyback, T (2618) Finland 2012
}) (7. f4 $6 {Of course, White would love to get away with this move, but we
should always meet it with a timely strike in the centre} Bxd4 (7... d5 $5) 8.
cxd4 d5 9. e5 Qg6 {[%cal Rc6b4] Black gets a tremendous initiative.} 10. a3 Qe4
11. Qd2 Nf5 12. Kf2 Nxe3 13. Qxe3 Qxd4 $17 {0-1 (56) Winawer,S-Englisch,B
Leipzig 1877}) 7... d5 {This is the point. With his last move, Black
eliminates White's space advantage and obtains a comfortable piece play.} 8.
O-O ({Another option is} 8. Bf3 {when Black should probably opt for IQP type
of position.} Bxd4 (8... Ne5 $5 {is also possible.}) 9. cxd4 ({After} 9. Bxd4
Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. cxd4 dxe4 12. Bxe4 c6 $15 {White struggles in the
endgame. 0-1 (34) Fluegel,E-Riemann,F Leipzig 1877}) 9... dxe4 10. Bxe4 Bf5 11.
Nc3 (11. Bf3 O-O-O 12. Qb3 Be6 $15 {[%cal Ge6d5] 0-1 (25) Kruskic,M (2305)
-Ascic,P (2396) Zupanja 2008}) 11... Bxe4 12. Nxe4 Qg6 13. Ng3 O-O (13... O-O-O
$5 $15) 14. O-O Rad8 $15 {White cannot compensate the weakness of his isolated
pawn. 0-1 (51) Suslin,A (2170)-Tydykov,A (2281) Prokopevsk 2012}) (8. exd5 $6
Nxd5 9. O-O Nxe3 10. fxe3 Qh6 $17 {Black has a better pawn structure and
