{[%evp 0,26,28,34,37,27,0,-15,-15,-15,41,41,17,31,17,12,25,-9,-16,-18,-1,-108,
-101,-117,-168,-160,-160,-168,-206]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5
5. Be3 Qf6 6. c3 Nge7 7. Nc2 Bb6 $5 {White's unpretentious 7th move has some
devilish logic behind it. Just like the 7.g3 line, white is hoping to
establish a firm grip on the d5-square, which would make Black's position
slightly cramped. Although this is a fine idea, and it is true that White's
knight would be ideally placed on e3, there are some tactical hurdles that
White simply cannot overcome. Even in the main line that goes 7...Bxe3 8.Nxe3
Qe5 9.Nd2 d5! Black should be able to solve his opening problems. However, I
will be proposing a setup that aims to make it difficult for the white knight
to even reach the e3-square. The move I will be proposing is 7...Bb6, after
which the positions will largely resemble the main line with 7.Bc4. Moreover,
it should be noted that another interesting way of going about the same idea
is 7...d6!?. In any case, analysis and experience show that White simply
cannot achieve his aims} 8. Nba3 {With this move white aims for quick
queenside development and pressure against the c7-pawn} ({White can also try
for rapid kingside development and control over the centre with} 8. Be2 $5 O-O
9. O-O Rd8 10. Bxb6 axb6 11. Ne3 {It seems that White is just in time to
prevent Black from playing d7-d5.} d5 $1 $146 {Nevertheless! Black's piece
activity is more than enough compensation for the pawn.} (11... d6 12. Na3 Be6
13. Nb5 Rac8 14. Nd5 $14 {1-0 (20) Strikovic,A (2520)-Cobb,J (2321) Dos
Hermanas 2004}) 12. exd5 Be6 13. Bf3 (13. c4 Qxb2 $13) 13... Ne5 14. c4 c6 15.
Nc3 Nxf3+ 16. Qxf3 Qxf3 17. gxf3 cxd5 $11 {Black regains the pawn and shakes
loose White's grip over the d5-square}) ({The main point of 7...Bb6 can be
appreciated after} 8. Bxb6 axb6 9. Ne3 Qe5 10. Nd2 d5 $11 {[%csl Ga8][%cal
Ga8a1] This is an improved version of the mainline (7...Bxe3) since Black has
opened the a-file for his rook. ½-½ (33) Gheorghiu, F-Spassky, B Marianske
Lazne 1962}) ({Dubious is} 8. Nd2 $6 {since it allows} d5 {in a comfortable
redaction.}) 8... O-O {The most natural move and a good one. However, to get a
better idea of what kind of positions White is aiming for (and which ones we
should avoid), see the variations below} (8... Qg6 9. Nb5 Qxe4 10. Be2 a6 11.
Bxb6 axb5 12. Bxc7 Qxg2 13. Bf3 Qg6 14. Qd2 $44 {White's initiative is very
dangerous.}) (8... Qe5 9. Be2 Qxe4 10. Bxb6 axb6 11. Nb5 Kd8 12. Ne3 d6 13. O-O
$44 {With tremendous compensation.}) (8... Bxe3 $6 9. Nxe3 a6 10. Be2 d6 11.
O-O $14 {Black does not have counterplay.}) 9. Nb5 (9. Nc4 $6 {the knight
wanders aimlessly while Black continues to prepare the central break} Qg6 10.
Nd2 d5 11. Qe2 dxe4 12. Bxb6 axb6 13. Nxe4 Re8 $19 {0-1 (13) Yantorno,J (1857)
-Hungaski,R (2505) Legislatura Open 2019}) (9. Bxb6 axb6 10. Nb5 {It seems
Black does not have a natural way of protecting the c7-pawn. However, the
queen is able to do the job long enough until the white knight can be driven
away from b5} Qe5 11. Ne3 (11. Qe2 {In this position the computer suggests
some interesting alternatives that do not involve getting rid of White's
annoying knight on b5, but I still like the thematic idea of driving the
knight away by means of ...Na7} Na7 (11... d5 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. O-O-O $14) (
11... Ra4 $5 12. f3 d5 $11) 12. Nbd4 c5 13. Nf3 Qe6 14. g3 Nac6 15. Ng5 Qg6 16.
f4 d5 $15 {and Black already took control over the game in Skoberne, J (2501)
-Szabo,K (2520) Budapest 2008}) 11... d5 12. exd5 Rd8 13. Bc4 Be6 14. dxe6 (14.
O-O Nxd5 $11) (14. Qe2 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Qxe2+ 16. Bxe2 Bxd5 17. Nxc7 Rxa2 18. Rxa2
Bxa2 {and the players agreed to a draw in the game Campora, D (2550)-Milos, G 
(2560) Sao Paulo 1993}) 14... Rxd1+ 15. Rxd1 fxe6 16. O-O $44 {White has
enough compensation to keep the balance, but not more than that.}) 9... Ba5 $1
$146 {This move buys enough time for Black to kick the knight out of b5 and
then proceed with the ...d7-d5 pawn break.} (9... Qe5 10. Bd3 Bxe3 (10... Ng6
11. O-O $16 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) (10... a6 11. f4 $16) 11. Nxe3 d5 (11... a6 12. Ng4
$16) 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Bxh7+ Kxh7 14. Qxd5 $16) (9... d6 10. Bxb6 cxb6 11. Nc7
Rb8 12. Ne3 $14) (9... d5 10. Bxb6 cxb6 11. Nc7 Rb8 12. Nxd5 $14) 10. b4 (10.
Bd3 d5 $11) (10. Qd2 a6 11. Nbd4 d5 $11) 10... a6 11. Nbd4 (11. bxa5 axb5 12.
Bxb5 Qxc3+ $15) 11... Bb6 12. Bc4 (12. Bd3 Ne5 13. Be2 d5 $11) 12... Ne5 13.
Bb3 d5 14. exd5 a5 15. bxa5 (15. a3 axb4 16. cxb4 Rd8 17. O-O Nxd5 $15) (15.
O-O $2 a4 $19) 15... Bxa5 16. Ne2 Nf5 17. O-O Re8 18. Qd2 Bd7 $44 {Black has a
nagging pressure due to white's numerous pawn weaknesses and more passive
pieces. In my opinion, Black has more than adequate compensation. The engine
happens to agree with me} *

