c3 Nge7 7. Bc4 Bb6 {This is not the most common move in this position (that
would be 7...b6, 7...Ne5, 7...0-0 or 7...Qg6), but I believe it leads to a
healthy position for Black with straight-forward play. Black's idea is to
prepare the ...d7-d5 pawn break!} 8. O-O O-O 9. Na3 {Now that Black has
castled he will go about preparing the ...d7-d5 pawn break. White has two ways
of creating problems for Black: 1) By putting pressure on c7 by means of the
transfer of a knight to b5 and 2) By preparing the f2-f4 advance. In the
variations that follow we will see both sides struggle to carry out their
respective idea, when I believe Black will ultimately have the better claim.} (
9. Nc2 Qg6 {A familiar theme when white prepares to play f2-f4. Black puts
pressure on e4 and prepares ...d7-d5. The queen is aggressively placed on g6
