15. bxa3 Qd6 16. Ne6 fxe6 17. dxe6 Nd3 $13) 10... h6 (10... d5 11. Bg5) 11. Ne2
Na5 12. Nf4 Nxc4 13. Nxc4 $13) 10. Nac2 ({After a slow move like} 10. Kh1 {
Black can even prepare ...f7-f5. For instance,} Qg6 11. f3 Kh8 12. Nac2 f5 13.
exf5 Nxf5 14. Nxf5 Bxf5 $11 {0-1 (50) Jodorcovsky,P-Dos Santos,R/San Rafael
1992/EXT 98}) ({White should not get too excited about the prospect of winning
a pawn after} 10. Ndb5 a6 11. Nxd6 Bxe3 (11... Rd8 $2 12. e5 $1 $18) 12. Nxc8 (
12. fxe3 Qg6) 12... Raxc8 (12... Nxc8 13. fxe3 Qg5 14. Bxf7+ Rxf7 15. Rxf7 Kxf7
16. Qb3+ Kg6 17. Qxb7 $18) 13. fxe3 Qg6 $44 {gave Black tremendous
compensation in Vink,N (2335)-Solleveld,M (2414) Leeuwarden 2001} (13... Qg5 $5
) 14. Qf3 (14. Qc2 Ne5 15. Bb3 b5 $44 {0-1 (66) Kerstens,D-Solleveld,M/Leiden
1998}) 14... b5 15. Be2 (15. Bb3 Na5 $5 {This move is a novelty. Practice has
shown that in such positions the pressure on f7 is very annoying. After
exchanging the b3-bishop, Black will enjoy better long-term perspectives.}) ({
Worse is} 15. Bd5 $6 Ne5 16. Qf4 Nd3 17. Qh4 Nxd5 18. exd5 Nxb2 $17 {when
Black's advantage is obvious.}) 15... Rcd8 16. Rad1 Ne5 (16... Qe6 $5 17. c4 b4
18. Nc2 Ne5 $44 {1/2-1/2 (25) Bergmann,M-Krol,W/IECG 2004/Telechess CBM 119})
17. Qf4 Qe6 18. b3 N7g6 19. Qg3 {So far, we have been following the game Vink,
N (2335)-Solleveld,M (2414) Leeuwarden 2001. At this point, I suggest the
following novelty:} Qc6 $1 $146 20. c4 Qc5 21. Nc2 bxc4 22. bxc4 Rxd1 (22...
Qa5 23. Rd5 $132) (22... Nxc4 23. Nd4 $132) 23. Rxd1 Qa5 24. Nd4 (24. Rd5 Qxa2
$17) 24... c5 $1 (24... Qxa2 25. c5 $13) 25. Nf5 Qxa2 $15 {White does not have
