{[%evp 0,22,28,31,37,17,9,23,23,23,23,0,1,-1,17,17,22,14,3,7,-8,-6,-6,-23,-7]} 
1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nxc6 bxc6 {This idea first
caught my attention after I saw an article published by Dutch IM Robert Ris.
Given how that work was published several years ago, I have since updated Mr.
Ris' excellent analysis and expanded upon it. Although this is a far cry from
being the main line (as opposed to 5...Qf6), I have noticed a trend in its
favour. I believe this is due to the dry endgames Black must often face after 5.
..Qf6 6.Qf3. But with this move order, not only is Black able to avoid this
annoying variation but also strive for more active development. Quite often
Black is able to develop the queen to h4, which leaves the f6-square available
for the knight. By far White's main move is 6.Bd3, but I will also discuss
some minor alternatives.} 6. Nc3 $5 {This move makes a lot of sense since it
takes the sting out of the ...Qh4 idea. It would seem that the best option for
black is to transpose to a favourable version of the 5...Qf6 6.Qf3 line, since
in that line white's strongest idea is to play the knight manoeuvre Nd2-b3, in
order to harass black's dark-squared bishop.} (6. Qf3 {White anticipates the
imminent attacks upon the f2 and e4 pawns. However, the queen may turn out to
be misplaced compared to the 5...Qf6 line, since there will be no queen trade
in sight} d5 $1 {Opening a diagonal for the bishop to attack the queen} 7. exd5
Nf6 (7... cxd5 $2 8. Bb5+ $16) 8. Qe2+ (8. dxc6 $2 Bg4 9. Qd3 Qe7+ 10. Be2 Rd8
11. Qb5 O-O $19) (8. h3 O-O 9. Be2 cxd5 $15 {Black recovers the pawn and
maintains an active position.}) 8... Kf8 $44 {the question now becomes whether
White's lagging development will be enough compensation for the pawn. As the
variations illustrate the answer seems to be a resounding "yes", which is why
White desperately tries to trade off the queens even if it means giving back
the pawn.} 9. Be3 (9. dxc6 $6 Ng4 10. Be3 Nxe3 11. fxe3 Qg5 $36) (9. Nc3 cxd5
10. Bf4 c6 $132) 9... Bxe3 10. Qxe3 cxd5 11. Nd2 Qe7 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 $11 {
was a pleasant endgame for Black in the game Burg, T (2449)-L'Ami, E (2620)
Vlissingen 2010}) (6. Bc4 $6 {The bishop will turn out to be misplaced on c4,
since once the black queen arrived on h4 it will x-ray it and increase the
strength of an eventual ...d7-d5 pawn break} Qh4 {[%cal Rg8f6,Rf6g4] Black has
a powerful initiative. Robert Ris illustrates this with some very convincing
variations} 7. O-O (7. Qf3 $6 d5 $1 8. Bd3 (8. exd5 $2 Qxc4 $19) 8... Nf6 9.
exd5 (9. Bf4 Bg4 10. Qg3 Qxg3 11. Bxg3 dxe4 $17) 9... Ng4 10. g3 (10. Qe2+ Kd8
$19) 10... Qe7+ 11. Be3 Bxe3 12. fxe3 Ne5 13. Qe4 Rb8 14. b3 Rb4 15. c4 cxd5
16. Qxd5 Bb7 $19 {is a good example of how Black can gain several tempi on the
misplaced bishop on c4 and develop a devastating initiative.}) (7. Qe2 {
Keeping an eye on the bishop} Nf6 8. Nc3 (8. e5 Nd5 $13) 8... O-O 9. O-O (9. g3
Qh3 10. Bg5 Ng4 11. f3 d5 $1 $17) 9... d5 $1 10. exd5 Re8 11. Qd3 Bd6 $40 {
[%cal Rf6g4] Black's initiative is truly overpowering. The knight is coming to
g4 no matter what! For example} 12. h3 (12. g3 Qh3 13. Qf3 Bg4 14. Qg2 Qh5 $17)
12... Ng4 13. dxc6 (13. Bd2 Ne5 14. Rae1 Ba6 $1 $17) 13... Ne5 14. Re1 Nf3+ $19
) 7... Nf6 8. g3 (8. Qf3 $6 {once again runs into} d5 9. Bd3 dxe4 10. Re1 O-O
11. Bxe4 Ng4 $19) (8. Nd2 O-O (8... Ng4 $6 9. Nf3 Nxf2 10. Qe2 Nh3+ 11. Kh1
Nf2+ $11) 9. Nf3 Qxe4 $15 {Black is a pawn up and should be able to finish
developing without too many inconveniences.}) (8. Nc3 $2 Ng4 $19 {0-1 (16)
Sirena,G (2092)-Moroni,L (2559) Chianciano Terme 2018}) 8... Qh3 9. Qf3 (9. Be2
h5 $19 {[%cal Rf6g4] White is simply getting mated}) 9... O-O 10. Nc3 d5 ({
a more moderate approach to the position can also be considered} 10... d6 $5
11. Qg2 Qh5 12. Be2 Bg4 13. Bxg4 Nxg4 14. Kh1 f5 $40 {and Black still had a
powerful initiative in the game Plat,V (2470)-Navara,D (2708) Brno 2013}) 11.
exd5 Bg4 12. Qg2 (12. Qd3 Bh5 $19 {[%cal Rf6g4] again we see that when the
knight managed to get to g4 it leads to a devastating attack for Black, as in
the game Odeev, H (2405)-Aghamaliyev, C (2523) Konya 2011}) 12... Qh5 13. Re1 ({
A way to survive would have been} 13. Be3 {Nevertheless, after} Bf3 14. Be2
Bxe2 15. Nxe2 Bxe3 16. fxe3 cxd5 {White faces huge problems due to his cramped
structure and unsecured king.}) ({The move} 13. h4 {does not help either -} Bf3
14. Qh3 cxd5 $17 {Black's advantage is obvious.}) 13... Bf3 14. Be2 (14. Qf1
Ng4 $19 {the threats on h2 and f2 seal the deal}) 14... Rae8 15. Qxf3 (15. Qf1
Ng4 $19) 15... Qxf3 16. Bxf3 Rxe1+ 17. Kg2 cxd5 18. Nxd5 Nxd5 19. Bxd5 Re2 $19
{Black has a winning material advantage and will soon activate the rooks. the
game is over.}) 6... Qf6 7. Qf3 (7. Qd2 Ne7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Ng6 $11 {[%cal
Gg6e5] Black has an easy game. Later on, he can develop a kingside initiative.
A possible plan is ...Ne5, ...d7-d6, ...Qg6, and ...f7-f5.0-1 (48) Gonzalez
Menendez,I (2430)-Korneev,O (2554) Lugo 2009}) 7... d6 8. Na4 ({A high-profile
game saw} 8. Qg3 {The reaction of the World Champion was very instructive -}
Qg6 9. Bd3 Nf6 10. Na4 Bd4 $1 {Before retreating to b6, Black aims at
provoking c2-c3 which weakens the d3-bishop.} 11. c3 Bb6 12. O-O Qxg3 13. hxg3
Ng4 14. Bf4 f6 $11 {[%cal Gg4e5] Black is ready to follow with ...Ne5 on the
next move. Later on, Magnus Carlsen won in a very nice style. 0-1 (59)
Radjabov,T (2784)-Carlsen,M (2835) Moscow 2012}) 8... Bd4 $1 {This is a key
idea for Black. If White continues to pursue the bishop, it will find safe
haven along the a1-h8 diagonal and leave the a4-knight out of the game} 9. Bd2
a5 (9... Bxb2 $2 10. Nxb2 Qxb2 11. Bc3 $18) 10. Be2 Qxf3 11. gxf3 (11. Bxf3 Ne7
12. Bc3 (12. c3 Bf6 $15 {[%csl Ra4]}) 12... Bxc3+ 13. Nxc3 O-O $11) 11... f5 $1
$15 {In these types of endgames (where White has doubled pawns on the f-file),
this pawn break is Black's most effective plan. Once the f-file is opened,
Black will get good counterplay against white's weak f and e pawns: 0-1 (42)
Yu, R (2571)-Yu, Y (2724) China 2015} *

