{[%evp 0,22,25,25,25,21,31,19,19,32,30,-7,-3,-7,3,19,26,1,11,7,-2,15,10,-14,
-14]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. Bd3 {This is
by far White's most natural move. By developing his bishop, White covers the
important e4-square. Before start fighting for the initiative, he is trying to
restrict Black's counterplay.} Qh4 7. Qe2 {This is probably White's most
flexible (and challenging) try. If Black's pieces get too threatening on the
kingside, White can choose to castle on the other side of the board.} ({
Another important line is} 7. Qf3 Nf6 8. Bf4 (8. Be3 Bxe3 9. Qxe3 {-
transposes to 7.Qe2}) ({In response to} 8. O-O {Black has a very nice reaction
-} Bd4 $3 {a deep manoeuvre to get the bishop involved with the kingside
initiative, while avoiding a possible queen trade following Qf4.} 9. h3 {
Designed to prevent ...Ng4.} ({After} 9. c3 {Black can follow with} Ng4 (9...
Be5 $6 10. g3 {[%csl Re5]} Qh3 11. Qg2 $16) 10. Bf4 (10. Qg3 Qxg3 11. hxg3 Bb6
$132 {[%csl Rf2,Gg4][%cal Yg4e5] Black keeps his initiative even in the
endgame.}) 10... Ne5 11. Qe2 (11. Bxe5 Bxe5 12. g3 Qe7 $132 {[%cal Yg7g6,Ye5g7]
}) 11... Nxd3 12. Qxd3 Bb6 13. Bg3 Qh5 14. Nd2 d6 15. Nc4 O-O $11 {Black
enjoys comfortable equality.}) (9. g3 Qh3 $132) (9. e5 Ng4 $1 $132 (9... Bxe5
$6 10. g3 $36 {[%csl Re5,Re8][%cal Yf1e1]})) 9... O-O 10. Nc3 (10. Na3 Re8 11.
c3 {and here it seems the Black bishop is in trouble, but there is a fantastic
dynamic solution which Black has at his disposal} d5 $3 (11... Bb6 $6 12. Bf4
d6 13. Rfe1 Be6 14. Nc4 Bxc4 15. Bxc4 $14 {and White had a stable edge in
Danin-Tjurin, Pardubice 2011.}) (11... Be5 $6 12. Nc4 $1 $14 {[%csl Re5] and
the bishop gets chopped down}) 12. exd5 (12. cxd4 dxe4 13. Bxe4 Qxe4 14. Qxe4
Rxe4 $11) 12... Be5 $44 {You will have to trust me when I tell you that
Black's initiative is quite powerful. Well, actually you don't have to trust me.
Here are some pretty cool computer lines} 13. Rd1 (13. dxc6 Bg4 $1 $36) (13.
Nc4 $2 Bg4 $1 $17 {[%csl Rf3]}) 13... h5 $1 {intending ...Bg4} (13... Nxd5 $2
14. Nc4 $16 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7,Re5]}) (13... cxd5 $6 14. Bb5 Rd8 (14... Re7 15. Nc4
$1 {[%csl Ra8]}) 15. Re1 Ne4 16. Bc6 Rb8 17. Nc4 Bf6 18. Ne3 Be6 19. Nxd5 Bxd5
20. Bxd5 Qxf2+ 21. Qxf2 Nxf2 22. Bxf7+ Kxf7 23. Kxf2 $14) 14. Be3 (14. Nc4 $2
Bg4 $1 15. hxg4 Qh2+ 16. Kf1 hxg4 17. Qf5 g6 18. Qg5 Bf4 $1 $19) (14. dxc6 $2
Bg4 15. hxg4 Qh2+ 16. Kf1 hxg4 $19) 14... cxd5 15. Bb5 Bg4 16. hxg4 Qh2+ 17.
Kf1 hxg4 18. Qf5 Re6 $17 {lack will continue with ...c7-c6 and ...Rae8 with
tremendous pressure}) (10. c3 Be5 11. Qf5 (11. Be3 d5 12. Nd2 Bg4 $17) 11... d6
12. Qg5 Qxg5 13. Bxg5 Nd7 14. f4 h6 15. Bh4 (15. fxe5 Nxe5 $1 $15) 15... Bxf4
16. Rxf4 g5 $11 {Black will regain the pieces, having secured the powerful e5
outpost for his knight}) (10. Nd2 d5 $11 {Black has nothing to complain about})
10... d6 11. Ne2 Bb6 12. Ng3 Re8 13. Re1 g6 14. Qf4 Qxf4 15. Bxf4 Nd7 $11 {
Black had a solid position while white still had to find a good way of
bringing the g3-knight back into play in the game: Danin, A (2543)-Makarov, M 
(2520) Olginka 2011.}) (8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bf4 d5 10. O-O (10. Bg3 Qg5 11. O-O Bg4
12. Qf4 Qxf4 13. Bxf4 Bb6 $11) 10... Bg4 11. Qg3 Qxg3 12. hxg3 Bb6 $11 {
these types of endgames are rarely a problem for Black. The worse pawn
structure is compensated by the pressure in the centre, which usually forces
white to take on d5 thus undoubling Black's pawns}) ({White could also try for
the queen trade right away} 8. Qg3 Qxg3 9. hxg3 Ng4 10. f3 (10. O-O O-O 11. Bf4
d6 12. Nd2 a5 13. a4 Be6 14. b3 f6 $11 {and the knight will be coming to e5,
with a very comfortable endgame for Black.}) 10... Nf2 11. Rh5 $1 (11. Rf1 $6
Nxd3+ 12. cxd3 d5 13. Nc3 Ba6 14. Kd2 dxe4 15. Nxe4 Bb6 $15) 11... Nxd3+ 12.
cxd3 Bd4 $1 {a typical manoeuvre to reroute the bishop to the kingside, while
putting pressure on White's queenside as well.} 13. Nc3 a5 (13... Rb8 14. Ne2
g6 15. Ra5 $132) (13... g6 14. Ra5 $132) 14. Bf4 g6 15. Rh2 d6 16. O-O-O h5 17.
Ne2 Bg7 $11 {with the bishop pair and the open b-file, Black is at least equal.
}) 8... d5 $1 9. exd5 (9. Bxc7 $2 dxe4 $19) (9. Nd2 O-O 10. O-O Bb6 11. h3 Be6
$11 {Mullon,J (2318)-Radulov,I (2359)/Clichy 2002}) 9... Nxd5 (9... O-O $6 10.
O-O Bg4 11. Qg3 Qxg3 12. Bxg3 Nxd5 13. h3 Be6 14. Nd2 $14 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7]}) 10.
Qe2+ (10. Bg3 Qe7+ 11. Qe2 Rb8 12. b3 Qxe2+ 13. Kxe2 Bd4 $15) 10... Be6 ({
Black can also embrace the worse structure with the hopes of achieving lively
piece play thanks to the open b-file} 10... Qe7 $5 11. Qxe7+ Bxe7 12. Be5 (12.
Bg3 $2 Bf6 13. c3 Rb8 $17) 12... f6 13. Bg3 Rb8 14. b3 h5 15. h4 Kf7 $11 {
Black's chances do not look worse to me.}) 11. Bg3 Qh6 12. O-O O-O 13. Nc3 ({
White should be careful if he tries to maintain the better structure since
this will allow Black's pieces to get quite active, especially the dark
squared bishop.} 13. Nd2 Rad8 (13... Nf4 $5) 14. Ne4 Bb6 15. Rae1 Nf4 16. Bxf4
Qxf4 17. b3 h6 $11 {the position remains balanced, but I would rather play
with Black since there is no easy way for White to take advantage of the
doubled isolated pawns, while Black's bishops are slicing across the board.})
13... Nxc3 14. bxc3 Bd6 $11 {each side suffers from its own set of doubled
isolated pawns, which makes the position completely balanced.}) (7. O-O Nf6 8.
Qf3 Bd4 {is just a transposition.}) 7... Nf6 8. h3 (8. Be3 Bxe3 9. Qxe3 O-O 10.
Nd2 {this is a useful maneuver to provide additional support to the kingside
by means of Nf3.} ({White can also opt to castle queenside with} 10. Nc3 Re8 ({
The tempting} 10... d5 $6 {fails to convince since White can enter a
favourable endgame after} 11. Qg3 $1 Qxg3 12. hxg3 dxe4 13. Nxe4 Re8 14. O-O-O
$1 $16 {White's avantage is obvious.}) 11. O-O-O d6 12. Qg3 ({After the
somewhat passive} 12. f3 {Black can play} Nd7 {[%cal Gd7c5,Gh4f6,Ga8b8]} 13.
Kb1 Nc5 14. g3 Qf6 15. h4 Rb8 $132 {It turns out that White's king is not safe
on the queenside.}) ({Premature is} 12. f4 $6 Nd5 13. Nxd5 cxd5 14. e5 dxe5 15.
fxe5 Bd7 $15 {Black has a better pawn structure and a safer king.}) 12... Qh5
13. f4 Rb8 14. h3 (14. Kb1 Qa5 $40) 14... Qc5 15. a3 (15. Qf3 Qb4 $17) 15...
Qb6 16. b3 Be6 $40 {Black has a dangerous initiative on the queenside.}) 10...
Re8 $1 {Keeps white guessing as to whether Black will strike with ...d7-d5 or
play along the dark-squared by means of ...d7-d6.} 11. O-O (11. Nf3 Qh5 12. O-O
d5 $36) 11... d6 {After} 12. Rfe1 {Black's best route to equality is} ({
Similar is} 12. Rae1 Nd5 13. Qg3 Qxg3 14. hxg3 Nb4 15. a3 Nxd3 16. cxd3 a5 $11)
12... Nd5 13. Qg3 Qxg3 14. hxg3 Nb4 15. a3 Nxd3 16. cxd3 a5 {[%cal Gc6c5,Gc8a6]
In this endgame, Black has more than sufficient counterplay to maintain 
equality.}) (8. e5 $2 Ng4 9. g3 Qh3 10. f4 O-O $17 {[%csl Gc5,Re1][%cal Yc5g1]}
) (8. O-O O-O 9. Nd2 (9. Be3 $2 Ng4 $17) 9... Re8 (9... Ng4 10. Nf3 Qh5 11. h3
Ne5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Kh1 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4]}) 10. Nf3 Qh5 11. h3 d6 {Black's
play is easier. He has pressure on e4 and different attacking ideas on the
kingside.}) (8. g3 $6 Qh3 $15 {White should not allow the black queen to sneak
into the kingside like this.}) 8... d5 $1 {This is the move that breathes new
life into black's position. Otherwise white would simply prepare queenside
castling and later win valuable attacking tempi at the expense of the black
queen} (8... O-O $6 9. g3 Qh5 10. g4 Qh4 (10... Qe5 $5) 11. Nd2 Ne8 12. Nb3 (
12. Nf3 Qe7 13. Bd2 Rb8 14. b3 d6 15. Bc3 Bb4 16. Bxb4 Rxb4 17. e5 c5 18. exd6
Qf6 19. d7 Bxd7 20. Ne5 $14 {1-0 Kovchan,A (2554)-Annaberdiev,M (2459)/Konya
2011/ (61)}) 12... Be7 13. Nd4 Bc5 14. Nf5 $14 {Motylev,A (2641)-Liang Chong 
(2531)/Moscow 2001/CBM 086 (1-0, 53). White has almost completed his
development and his pieces are actively posted..} Qd8 15. Bd2 Nd6 16. O-O-O
Nxf5 17. gxf5 Qh4 18. Rh2 Bd4 19. Rg1 Be5 20. Rhg2 $16 {1-0 Motylev,A (2641)
-Liang Chong (2531)/Moscow 2001/ (53)}) 9. g3 ({Black's main point can be
appreciated after} 9. exd5+ Kd8 $1 {[%cal Rh8e8]} 10. O-O Bxh3 11. dxc6 (11.
Qe5 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Bd6 13. Qf5 Qh2+ 14. Kf3 Re8 15. Bg5 Qh5+ 16. Kg2 Qh2+ 17.
Kf3 Qh5+ {1/2-1/2 Nataf-Istratescu, Saint Quentin 2014.}) (11. gxh3 $2 Qg3+ 12.
Kh1 Qxh3+ 13. Kg1 Re8 $19 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Rc5d6]} (13... Ng4 $2 14. Bf4))
11... Re8 12. Qd2 Bxg2 13. Kxg2 Qg4+ $11) 9... Qh5 10. Qxh5 (10. g4 $2 Bxg4 $19
) 10... Nxh5 11. Nc3 (11. e5 $6 Bd4 12. g4 (12. Nd2 Bxe5 $17) (12. Be2 g6 13.
Bxh5 gxh5 14. f4 Rg8 $17) 12... Nf4 13. Bxf4 Bxb2 14. Kd2 Bxa1 15. Nc3 Bxc3+
16. Kxc3 c5 $17 {0-1 (32) Nataf,I (2534)-Fressinet,L (2673) Pau 2008}) 11...
O-O (11... Nf6 12. Bf4 Bb4 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Bd2 Nxc3 15. Bxc3 Bxc3+ 16. bxc3
Be6 17. f4 O-O 18. Kf2 Rab8 19. f5 $14 {0-1 (68) Ivanchuk-Malakhov, Warsaw
2009.}) 12. Bd2 (12. exd5 cxd5 (12... Re8+ 13. Kf1 cxd5 14. Nxd5 Bb7 15. c4 Nf6
16. Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Rh2 Rad8 $44) 13. Nxd5 Bb7 14. c4 Rfe8+ 15. Kf1 Nf6 16.
Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Rh2 Bf3 $44) 12... Re8 13. Kf1 Bb7 14. Kg2 Nf6 $11 {the game
was balanced in Matos Garcia-Ris, Havana 2015.} *

