{[%evp 0,30,13,16,16,-5,24,-6,7,7,32,1,1,1,12,-20,-25,-15,7,-12,-25,-39,-56,
-29,-45,-35,-22,-53,-19,-38,12,6,10]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4
Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Nge7 {I really like this idea for Black. For one, it
steers clear of all the topical theoretical discussions currently taking place
in the 6...Nf6 variation, where White has been trying very hard, with the
obvious help of computers, to create problems for Black either by means of 7.
Bg5 or 7.Qe2. It seems Black is doing fine in both cases, but the road to
equality is far from obvious. Therefore, I will recommend this less trodden
path. This is a pet line of Kamsky and I have incorporated it into my own
repertoire with both colours. Black's idea is still to strike in the centre by
means of ...d7-d5, but only after having undermined white's e-pawn by means of
...f7-f5 first.} 7. Bg5 $6 {In general, when White plays the bishop to g5 is
it with the idea of developing the queen to d2 instead of e2. This has the
advantage of not blocking the bishop on f1 while preparing to castle
queenside. However, even though this is an interesting try against 6...Nf6, it
does not work so well with the knight on e7. Now the pin can be easily broken
by means of ...f7-f6.} ({The main line} 7. Qe2 {[%emt 0:00:09] is dealt with
in Chapter}) 7... f6 $1 (7... O-O $6 8. Qd2 f6 9. Be3 $1 $14 {this is a dream
position for white, since the bishop has come to e3 without the need to
put the queen on e2 where it blocks the f1-bishop}) 8. Bh4 O-O 9. Qd2 a5 $1
({Black should avoid passive moves that allow White to complete his
development and increase his pressure on the centre. For example:} 9... d6 $6
10. O-O-O Be6 11. Kb1 Qe8 12. f4 f5 13. exf5 Nxf5 14. Bf2 Bxf2 15. Qxf2 Qf7 16.
g3 $14 {the bishop now comes to g2 and the d5-square is firmly under control})
10. Bb5 {White has to do something about the imminent ...a5-a4 advance, which
would relegate the b3-knight to a terribly passive square} (10. O-O-O $6 a4 11.
Na1 a3 $17 {with the knight on a1 there is no need for words}) ({It might be
tempting to halt Black's a-pawn by means of} 10. Na4 Ba7 11. O-O-O d6 12. Kb1 (
12. Bc4+ Kh8 13. Kb1 Qe8 $1 $15 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Re8a4] a good way of trying
to take advantage of the knight on the rim}) 12... Be6 13. f4 Qe8 $1 14. Bf2
Bxf2 15. Qxf2 f5 16. exf5 Bxf5 17. Nc3 (17. g3 Nb4 $17 {[%csl Ra4] is one
example of how the knight may get into trouble}) 17... a4 18. Nd4 Nxd4 19. Qxd4
Qg6 20. Bd3 Bxd3 21. Rxd3 a3 $13) ({In his Scotch Database, IM Robert Ris
suggests a very interesting move -} 10. a4 {White is trying to restrict
Black's active possibility. At this point, we should be very careful not to
find ourselves doomed to passivity.} d6 11. O-O-O Be6 12. f4 {White is ready
to follow with Bf2, thus obtaining a stable advantage. Here, I suggest a new
idea} Nb4 $146 13. Bf2 Bxf2 14. Qxf2 Bxb3 15. cxb3 c6 $132 {[%cal Gd6d5] Black
wants to play d6-d5. White has active pieces and strong light-squared bishops.
On the other hand, Black has counterplay since the white king can get
vulnerable.}) 10... Ne5 {Aiming to displace the bishop by means of ...c7-c6,
which would renew the idea of ...a5-a4 as well as introduce the idea of ...
d7-d5} 11. f4 N5g6 12. Bf2 c6 $5 $146 {Black should make use of his slight
lead in development before White gets a chance to castle. At the expense, of
the bishop on b5, Black is able to carry out the ...d7-d5 pawn break quite
effectively.} 13. Bc4+ ({Worse is} 13. Bd3 a4 14. Nd4 d5 $15 {when Black is
already slightly better.}) 13... d5 14. exd5 Bxf2+ 15. Qxf2 b5 $1 {This is the
point of Black's play. White's minor pieces are clumsy and stumble over one
another, so Black will be able to displace them and recover the pawn.} 16. Bd3
a4 (16... b4 $6 17. Na4 Nxd5 18. g3 Re8+ 19. Kd2 $14 {the white king is
perfectly safe on d2 and Black is left with several weaknesses on the queenside.
Moreover, the knight on g6 is dominated.}) 17. Nd4 b4 18. Nce2 Nxd5 19. O-O (
19. Nxc6 Qd6 20. Ncd4 Ndxf4 $13) 19... Qd6 $13 {Black will continue by
developing the bishop to d7 and striving for control of the e-file.} *

