{[%evp 0,30,13,16,16,-5,24,-6,7,7,32,1,1,1,12,-20,-25,-15,7,-12,-25,-39,-56,
-29,-45,-35,-22,-53,-19,-38,12,6,10]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4
Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Nge7 7. Qe2 O-O 8. Be3 f5 9. exf5 $1 {This is likely to
be White's most challenging try. The point is to keep the knight on c3, from
where it will control d5 and make it hard for Black to carry out the ...d7-d5
idea.} ({Black is always happy to see the move} 9. Bxb6 {since it allows him
to activate the a8-rook by means of} axb6 {White's king will not be safe on
the queenside any longer.} 10. exf5 d5 11. O-O-O ({The attempt to protect the
pawn by means of} 11. g4 {is well met by the energetic} Nxf5 $1 {[%csl Re1]
[%cal Rf8e8,Re8e1]} 12. O-O-O (12. gxf5 Re8 $19) 12... Nd6 {The position
remains complicated but Black's counterplay is sufficient. For example:} 13.
Kb1 (13. Rxd5 Nb4 $132) (13. Nxd5 Rxa2 $132) 13... d4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Rxd4
Qf6 16. Qd2 Qxf2 $11) 11... Bxf5 12. Kb1 Qe8 {with the devilish idea of
playing ...Nb4 followed by ...Nxa2 and ...Qa4.} 13. a3 ({The move} 13. g3 $2 {
runs into Black's idea} Nb4 14. Rc1 (14. Nd4 Nxa2 15. Nxa2 Qa4 $19) 14... Nxa2
15. Nxa2 Rxa2 16. Kxa2 Qa4+ 17. Kb1 Ra8 18. Rd1 Qxb3 $19 {Black is winning.}) (
13. Nxd5 $2 {is losing after} Nxd5 14. Qxe8 Raxe8 15. Rxd5 Nb4 16. Rd2 Re1+ 17.
Nc1 Bxc2+ 18. Rxc2 Nxc2 19. Kxc2 Rxf2+ $19) 13... Qf7 14. f4 Rad8 15. Nb5 (15.
Qd2 $2 d4 16. Nb5 d3 $19) (15. g3 d4 $15) 15... Rd7 16. g3 d4 $13 {Black has
managed to bring all the pieces into the game and enjoys a nice space
advantage in the centre. Moreover, White's knight on b3 is misplaced, as quite
often occurs in this variation.}) (9. O-O-O {This is the move recommended by
Negi in his book "The Modern Scotch Opening". However, he seems to
underestimate Black's next move} f4 $1 {Black now aims to secure the e5-square
for his knight, while practically forcing the exchange of bishops. This will
activate Black's rook as well as highlight the fact that White will have many
pawns on light squares.} 10. Bxb6 axb6 11. Kb1 ({Negi suggests that White's
position is better after} 11. g3 {but further analysis shows that Black's play
along the dark squares should not be underestimated.} d6 12. gxf4 Rxf4 13. Rg1
Ne5 $15 {but Black was firmly in control in Kulkarni, R (2281)-Kamsky, G (2676)
Bastia 2017}) (11. Qd2 d6 12. Bc4+ Kh8 13. f3 Ne5 14. Be2 Be6 $13) ({White can
also try to avoid Black's clamp along the dark squares by playing} 11. e5 Ng6
12. Nd4 Nxd4 13. Rxd4 c6 $1 14. Qh5 (14. g3 b5 15. gxf4 Nxf4 16. Qg4 (16. Qd2
Qg5 17. Re4 (17. h4 Qxe5 $19) 17... Ne6 $15) 16... d5 $17) (14. h4 Qe7 15. Re4
Re8 $132 {[%csl Re5][%cal Ga8a5,Ga5e5,Ge8e5,Gg6e5]}) 14... Ra5 15. Bc4+ Kh8 16.
Re1 Re8 17. Rde4 d5 $1 $15 {thanks to the pin Black was able to activate his
light-squared bishop and assert his presence in the centre. Black's position
was already better in the game Diepeveen, V (2305)-Geenen, M (2215) Belgium 2014}
) 11... d6 12. f3 (12. Qd2 Kh8 13. g3 Bg4 14. Be2 f3 15. Bb5 Ne5 $13 {and the
e5-square has been secured for the knight}) ({Another game saw} 12. Qc4+ Kh8
13. Nb5 Ng6 14. Qc3 Bd7 15. f3 Rc8 16. Be2 Nce5 17. Na7 Ra8 18. Nb5 Rc8 19. Na7
Ra8 20. Nb5 Bxb5 21. Bxb5 c6 22. Be2 b5 $132 {and Black was in the driver's
seat in the game Royset, P (2234)-Tisdall, J (2423) Norway 2016}) 12... Be6 13.
Nd5 ({After} 13. Qd2 {Black should opt for} Bxb3 {An important exchange which
further weakens the position of White's king. If Black manages to exchange one
pair of knights, we will have a classical position with a strong knight
against a bad bishop.} 14. cxb3 Ne5 {A possible line would be} 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16.
Qxd5+ Kh8 17. Qxb7 $2 (17. b4 $13) 17... c6 {[%csl Rb7]} 18. Bc4 (18. Rc1 Rf7
$19) 18... Re8 $19 {And the queen is trapped.}) 13... Ne5 14. Qd2 Bxd5 15. exd5
Qd7 16. a3 Qa4 17. Qc3 Nf5 18. Nd4 Ne3 $15 {and Black's knights were dominant
in the game Liu,A (1969)-Corallo,M (2275) chess.com 2017}) (9. f4 fxe4 10.
O-O-O d5 11. Kb1 (11. Nxe4 a5 12. Bxb6 cxb6 13. Nc3 a4 14. Nd4 a3 15. b3 Rxf4
$17 {Black is simply up a pawn while the pawn on a3 guarantees Black long-term
initiative on the queenside.}) (11. Bxb6 $6 axb6 12. g3 Be6 13. Nxe4 {and now
in the game Thakur, A (2283)-Rzayev, B (2465) Al Ain 2013, Black could have
retained the extra pawn and the advantage with} Qc8 14. Ng5 (14. Nc3 Bg4 $17)
14... Bg4 15. Nf3 Rxa2 $17) 11... Bxe3 12. Qxe3 Bg4 13. Rd2 Qd6 $15 {black
retained the extra pawn and went on to win in the game Rangel, D (2278)-Perdomo,
L (2449) Rio de Janeiro 2018 5.Nb3 & 6...Nge7-9.Sidelines}) 9... Rxf5 $1 {
Black also does not want to distract attention from the fight for the d5-square
} 10. O-O-O $5 {This seems to be the most ambitious try.} ({As usual} 10. Bxb6
{is not dangerous for Black.} axb6 11. O-O-O Qf8 12. f3 Qf7 $11 {Black has
good perspectives on the queenside.}) (10. f4 Rf6 11. Bxb6 axb6 12. Qd2 d5 13.
O-O-O Bg4 $5 (13... Kh8 14. g3 Na5 15. Nxa5 Rxa5 {1/2-1/2 (15) Hungaski,R 
(2456)-Kamsky,G (2673) Chicago 2015} 16. Bg2 (16. Kb1) 16... c6 17. Kb1 Bg4 18.
Rde1 Nc8 19. Ne4 $14) 14. Be2 Bxe2 15. Qxe2 Rxf4 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Qe6+ Kh8 18.
Rxd5 Qf8 19. Kb1 Re8 $11 {If anyone must be careful here it should be White 
since the knight on b3 is father from the centre than its Black counterpart
and Black's rooks are also more active.}) 10... Re5 (10... d5 11. Qd2 $14) 11.
Qd2 (11. Qc4+ d5 12. Qf4 Bxe3+ 13. fxe3 $13) 11... Bxe3 12. fxe3 d6 13. Nd4 (
13. Bc4+ Kh8 14. Nd4 $13) 13... Bg4 14. Bc4+ Kh8 15. Rdf1 Ng8 $1 $132 {[%cal
Gg8f6] Once the knight gets to f6, then Black's control over the dark squares
and good centralization should be able to keep White's initiative at bay.} *

